Non-Communicable Diseases, Eight Key Points
GENÈVE - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart disease, stroke, cancer, diabetes and chronic respiratory diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, physical inactivity, unhealthy diet and excessive alcohol consumption increase the risk of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Yet despite widespread awareness of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It is in this context that NCD alliances networks met from December 9 to 11 at the second World NCD Alliance Forum in the United Arab Emirates.
Dans leur recherche de solutions visant à réguler les MNT, ils devraient s'inspirer du mouvement de lutte contre le SIDA.
Les personnes vivant avec et affectées par le VIH continuent de mener des interventions et leur forme unique de mobilisation a été essentielle dans les progrès accomplis.
Alors que la bataille n'est pas terminée, les militants du SIDA savent qu'ils peuvent remporter cette bataille.
De même, un mouvement de mobilisation contre les MNT peut faire reculer cette épidémie.
Pourtant en 2015, Richard Horton, le rédacteur en chef de la revue The Lancet, a décrit la communauté des MNT comme étant en attente « d'un électrochoc sur son esprit semi-comateux. » Il a ajouté : « Mais qui aura le courage de le lui administrer ? »
We believe there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
As global attention focuses on the prevention of NTDs, those seeking to control preventable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABC of AIDS activist organizations.
The first letter that the NTD community must consider is « A », as in activism.
Anyone over the age of 40 surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in « die-in » demonstrations at scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets, even shutting down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
On a worldwide level, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Next, the NCD Community must adopt a more ambitious approach to budgets - the "B" of the HIV/AIDS movement's strategy.
Civil organisation and grassroots activism can mobilise the initial energies, but the organisation and maintenance of a broad coalition requires money.
The HIV/AIDS movement was clear on this from the beginning and has pushed for resources to effectively support its awareness and empowerment activities.
« C » represents coalitions: movements fighting against AIDS have quickly realized that progress comes only with multiple supporters.
Activists have established links between people living with HIV and those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders from public authorities, in order to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The AIDS activism movement has also realized that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential for the spread of its support.
Thus, « D », the determining factor of success, was to 'draw attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make intelligent decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: as many factors that played a driving role in the HIV/AIDS crisis.
MNT are not less isolated in their causality and are also subject to a multisectoral approach to prevention.
Engagement - « E » - was what helped the HIV/AIDS movement gain such great influence.
Through strategic borrowing from the movement for the rights of people with disabilities, which championed the slogan « Nothing about us without us », HIV/AIDS advocates demanded the representation of existing bodies to address the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only UN agency with seats on its Governing Council intended for representatives of civil society.
This norm is so deeply embedded in the fight against HIV/AIDS that it would be almost unthinkable for an HIV/AIDS meeting to take place without community representation.
Prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives and "F" - framing the issue - is essential for the HIV/AIDS community to gain support from political leaders.
In particular, access to HIV/AIDS treatments has been presented as an issue of economic justice.
Formulating the narrative in this way leads to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the extent that more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
An equally important formulation of the issue for AIDS, a highly relevant question for the MNT movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community has worked hard to focus more on the lifestyle choices of people, rather than on attributing the responsibility of the state in providing healthcare and in eliminating legal discrimination.
In the debate on AIDS, gender - the "G" of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a "disease of gays," and gender identity was embedded from the beginning in the DNA of the AIDS activism movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to examine how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
The genre, therefore, must become a focal point for prevention efforts against STIs.
Finally, « H » - human rights - are the foundation of the response to AIDS.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination in workplaces, schools, and medical centers.
The strategic dispute allowed for equality under the law to be ensured.
The movement against AIDS has refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The MNT movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that are unable to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods for children.
We could continue throughout the alphabet the list of lessons learned from the fight against AIDS, but it seems appropriate to close it on "H", given that human rights provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk for HIV.
The same is true for NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Aujourd'hui, with 70 % of the planet in danger of premature death due to preventable diseases, « these people » represent a large number of us.
The MNT and HIV/AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
